📖 Domain Understanding¶

Background¶

Handwritten digit recognition is a pivotal domain within the broader field of computer vision and pattern recognition. In essence, the task involves training machine learning models to accurately classify and discern numerals inscribed by hand. Beyond its inherent academic significance, the practical applications of this domain span various industries, including finance, postal services, and document analysis. For instance, in the realm of banking, automated reading of handwritten checks can streamline processes, while postal services leverage digit recognition for mail sorting.

Research¶

Main Question:

How can we enhance the accuracy and interpretability of neural networks for recognizing handwritten digits?

Sub-Questions:

  1. What types of neural network structures, like feedforward networks or convolution networks, work best for recognizing handwritten digits?
  2. How do techniques like dropout and L1/L2 regularization help prevent the model from learning too much from the training data?
  3. Could combining predictions from multiple models through ensemble methods lead to better results?

Research methods¶

Research Method Description
Literature Review This method involves reviewing existing articles, documents, and reports. It provides a comprehensive understanding of existing knowledge and research findings in the field.
Available Product Analysis This method consists of analyzing and evaluating existing products or services in the market. It helps identify trends, strengths, and areas for improvement in current offerings.

Introduction

A neural network is a method in artificial intelligence that teaches computers to process data in a way that is inspired by the human brain. It is a type of machine learning process, called deep learning, that uses interconnected nodes or neurons in a layered structure that resembles the human brain. Artificial neural networks (ANNs) are comprised of a node layers, containing an input layer, one or more hidden layers, and an output layer. Each node, or artificial neuron, connects to another and has an associated weight and threshold. If the output of any individual node is above the specified threshold value, that node is activated, sending data to the next layer of the network. Otherwise, no data is passed along to the next layer of the network.

Optimal Neural Network Structures

The research demonstrates that convolutional neural networks (CNNs) outperform other structures like feedforward networks when recognizing handwritten digits. As Akshat (2019) explains, when dealing with image inputs, each pixel possesses a distinc weight, resulting in an impractical number of parameters for standard image sizes in feedforward networks. For instance, a 227x227 image would entail 227x227x3 parameters, leading to a vast number of neurons in a single layer. However, CNNs have have a kernel and the weights are shared as the kernel moves horizontally and vertically acrosss the image. Additionally, operations like maxpooling further contribute to parameter reduction, ensuring the efficiency of CNNs in handling image-related tasks. This insight underscores the significance of optimal neural network structures, emphasizing the superiority of CNNs, particularly in the context of recognizing handwritten digits.

Preventing Overfitting with Regularization Techniques

My findings reveal that techniques like dropout and L1/L2 regularization play pivotal roles in preventing overfitting during training. By introducing dropout, which randomly deactivates neurons, and applying regularization penalties to weights, the models strike a balance between accuracy and generalization, avoiding undue reliance on the training data.

Ensemble Methods for Improved Predictions

Combining predictions from multiple models through ensemble methods proves to be a powerful strategy for boosting recognition accuracy. Combining diverse models to mitigate individual weaknesses results in more robust and accurate predictions.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this research underscores the pivotal role of architecture, regularization techniques, ensemble methods for recognizing handwritten digits. These insights contribute not only to the academic understanding of neural network dynamics but also offer practical guidance for optimizing models in real-world applications. The pursuit of more accurate and interpretable models in handwritten digit recognition remains a dynamic and evolving field, with ongoing opportunities for exploration and refinement.

📋 Data Requirements¶

Data Elements¶

  • Numerical Data:

    • Data Type: Numerical
    • Example: Pixel intensity values
    • Units: Grayscale values (0 to 255)
    • Range: 0 to 255

  • Categorical Data:

    • Data Type: Categorical
    • Example: Digit labels
    • Categories: 0 to 9

  • Image Data:

    • Data Type: Image
    • Derivation: Composed of pixel intensity values
    • Size: 28x28 pixels
    • Content: Grayscale representation of handwritten digits
    • Digit Range: 0 to 9 (The digit within the image should be one of the numbers from 0 to 9)

MNIST Dataset¶

The MNIST database (Modified National Institute of Standards and Technology database) is a large database of handwritten digits that is commonly used. It was created by re-mixing samples from NIST's original datasets. The MNIST database contains 60,000 training images and 10,000 testing images. Half of the training set and half of the test set were taken from NIST's training dataset, while the other half of the training set and the other half of the test set were taken from NIST's testing dataset. The set of images in the MNIST database was created in 1994 as a combination of two of NIST's databases: Special Database 1 and Special Database 3. Special Database 1 and Special Database 3 consist of digits written by high school students and employees of the United States Census Bureau, respectively.

The orginal dataset is in a format that can be difficult to use. The dataset that I will be using is provided from Joseph Redmon in a CSV format. I will be using 2 files - mnist_train.csv which is the training set, and mnist_test.csv which is the testing set. Each row consists of 785 values: the first values is the label (a number from 0 to 9) and the remaining 784 values are pixel values (a number from 0 to 255).

def display_samples(data, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for i in range(10):
        plt.subplot(2, 5, i+1)
        plt.imshow(data.iloc[i, 1:].to_numpy().reshape(28, 28), cmap='gray')
        plt.title(f"Label: {data.iloc[i, 0]}")
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

def display_samples_by_label(data, label, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    
    data_label = data[data.iloc[:, 0] == label].head(10)
    
    for i in range(10):
        plt.subplot(2, 5, i+1)
        plt.imshow(data_label.iloc[i, 1:].to_numpy().reshape(28, 28), cmap='gray')
        plt.title(f"Label: {data_label.iloc[i, 0]}")
        plt.axis('off')
    
    plt.suptitle(title)

Let's dig deeper into the world of handwritten numbers by looking at 10 different samples for each digit. Each person has their own unique way of writing, but it's interesting to note that all the digits we're studying come from people in the United States. This might mean they were taught to write in a similar way.

But here's the cool part: handwriting isn't just about the person. It also depends on the situation. Imagine filling out a form in a hurry – your writing might look different, and you might even have trouble recognizing it yourself!

Our dataset comes from real documents, making it realistic but sometimes tricky. There are moments where even a person might struggle to figure out which digit is which. This mix of personal styles and real-world situations adds a layer of complexity. It highlights the challenge of creating a smart system that can tell the difference between digits, no matter how they're written.

It is important to note these downsides of the dataset and the task before putting into a machine learning model. Knowing the pitfalls and understanding what we can control and what not is crucial for each task.

The first digit is the 0. Zeros are usually easy to write. It can be an opened or closed circle, and slimmer or wider cirlce. When in a rush, if the circle is not closed and the top goes a bit higher, it can be easily interpreted as a 6.

In [ ]:

This can differ from person to person, and the way they are taught. if the digit is written with 2 lines, without the line in the bottom, it can be easily mistaken for a 7.

In summary, each digit boasts its own unique handwriting, and it's highly unlikely to find two identical instances. The variability in how people write digits, coupled with the diverse circumstances under which they're written, can make interpretation challenging. Even within our sampled data, we encounter instances of digits that can be perplexing.

Take, for example, the resemblance between some 7s and 1s. Without the context of knowing it's a sample of the digit 7, there's a real risk of confusing it with a 1. This realization becomes crucial for our process – acknowledging that not every digit in our dataset is crystal clear. Nevertheless, armed with this insight, our goal remains the same: to train a model capable of successfully distinguishing these varied handwritten digits.

Feedforward neural network with 6 layers¶

The feedforward neural network using Keras is designed for simplicity and ease of use. The architecture consists of several dense layers, each followed by a rectified linear unit (ReLU) activation function, which introduces non-linearity and allows the network to learn complex patterns. The model follows a sequential structure, with the layers stacked one after the other. Although straightforward, this model showcases the foundational elements of neural network design, making it suitable for introductory purposes or tasks where a relatively simple architecture is sufficient.

🧬 Modelling¶

The model we are going to create is a feedforward neural network using the Keras Sequential API. This is one of the simplest approaches in neural networks. The model consists of three dense fully connected layers with ReLU functions and dropout layers for regularization. Regularization, ReLU (Rectified Linear Unit), and dropout are techniques used in neural networks to improve their generalization performance, prevent overfitting, and enhance training stability.

ReLU is an activation function commonly used in neural networks. It replaces all negative values in the input with zero and leaves positive values unchanged. Mathematically, the ReLU activation function is defined as f(x)=max(0,x). ReLU reduces non-linearity to the model, allowing it to learn complex relationships in the data. Recognizing digits involves learning complex, non-linear relationships between pixel values in the input images and the corresponding digit labels.

For the initializer, we are using He initialization. It is a specific weigth initialization technique and helps with the stable and efficient training of deep neural networks, especiall those using acitvation functions like ReLU.

To prevent overfitting, there are a couple of techniques to be implemented. The regularization for each neural network and each task can differ a lot. It is important to find a suitable balance, where the model is performing well, but is not overfitting. One of the ways to prevent overfitting and enhance the model robustness is dropout. It works by randomly setting to 0 a fraction of the neurons in a layer during each training iteration. Another one of the techniques is the kernel regularization L2. It forces the model to focus on essential features and avoid fitting the noise in the training data.

The last layer uses the softmax activation function, indicating that the model is designed for a multi-class classification task with 10 output classes.

In [ ]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), input_shape=(28*28,)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.1))
model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

The next function provides an informative overview of the architecture of the neural network. The model consists of 4 layers - Dense, Dropout and Softmax. The Dense layers are fully connected layers. Dropout layers introduce regularization to prevent overfitting. Softmax is the output layer.

The next plot that we are going to do is vital for our process. It is going to help us determine if the model is learning well and if it is overfitting. The plot visualizes the training and validation loss across different epochs. The training loss curve indicates how well the model is fitting the training data over successive epochs, aiming to minimize the loss. On the other hand, the validation loss reflects the model's performance on a separate portion of the data not used for training, providing insigths into its generalization to new, unseen samples. Ideally, both training and validation loss should decrease over epochs. If the training loss decreses while the validation loss increses, it could be a sign of overfitting. Additionally, if lines remain high or decrease slowly, the model might be underfitting.

This plot has helped me a lot in the creation of an accurate neural network model. When I initially started this notebook, I created a model that had no regularization. Looking at this plot after every change I make of the parameters in the model or the data, helps me a lot to determine if I am in the right direction and if the model is learning well.

In summary, the loss plot is a valuable diagnostic tool for assessing the model's training progress and generalization performance. It helps identify potential issues and guides adjustments to the model architecture or training parameters.

Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) with 9 layers¶

The Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is again constructed using the Keras Sequential API. Unlike the simplicity of a feedforward network, CNN is specialized for tasks involving grid-like data such as images. This architecture employs convolutional layers that systematically scan the input image, capturing local patterns through convolutional operations. These convolutional layers are interleaved with max-pooling layers, reducing spatial dimensions and preserving important features. The network is designed to learn hierarchical representations of the input data, enhancing its ability to recognize complex visual patterns.

🧹 Preprocessing¶

For the preprocessing step here, we need to reshape the images again. CNNs are particularly effective for image-related tasks, and their input format typically involves a three-dimensional structure representing the image dimensions along with the number of channels. So, the reshaped datasets X_train_cnn and X_test_cnn are now three-dimensional arrays representing images suitable for input into a CNN.

In [ ]:
X_train_cnn = X_train.reshape((-1, 28, 28, 1))
X_test_cnn = X_test.reshape((-1, 28, 28, 1))

🧬 Modelling¶

As mentioned, CNN is a more complex neural network model, so let's think of CNN as a smart robot learning to recognize handwritten numbers. With that said, now we are going to break down each part:

  • Layer 1: The robot looks at the picture and spots simple shapes. It uses 32 different filters to focus on different feauters like strokes and curves.
  • Max Pooling 1: The robot takes a step back and looks at the bigger picture, finding the most important indormation, then it compresses the image a bit to keep the important details.
  • Layer 2: We are going deeper. The robot tries to understand more complex patterns and now it uses 64 filters to capture more features.
  • Max Pooling 2: We are zooming out again. The robot reduces the image size while keeping the essential features intact.
  • Layer 3: The robot goes even deeper.
  • Flatten Layer: The robot organizes all the information.
  • Fully Connected Layer 1: The robot looks at the overall picture and tries to understand what it sees. At this layer, we are also adding regularization to prevent overfitting.
  • Dropout Layer: The robot wants to make sure it is not getting too obseessed with tiny details. It randomly ignores some of its observations (40% of them) to stay more balanced.
  • Fully Connected Layer 2 (Output Layer): The robot is ready to give an answer. It makes a final decision and picks the most likely answer.

This explanation is as simplified as possible, so my work is transparent and understandable by everyone. CNNs can be hard to understand, but once you do, they are extremely useful and go way deeper than the feedforward networks.

In [ ]:
cnn = models.Sequential()

# First conv layer followed by max pooling
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', input_shape=(28, 28, 1)))
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2)))

# Second conv layer followed by max pooling
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'))
cnn.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2))

# Third conv layer
cnn.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'))

# Fully connected layers
cnn.add(layers.Flatten())
cnn.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
cnn.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
cnn.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) with 16 layers¶

Now, let's discuss our final model in this notebook. This neural network is a CNN with 16 layers, designed to excel in recognizing handwritten digits. Our main goal throughout this project has been to understand how neural networks work, and this model, being more complex, has proven to be effective. We won't delve into the details of each layer's creation, as we've covered that before. Instead, let's focus on the overall architecture and its success in handling the nuances of recognizing handwritten digits.

🧬 Modelling¶

Let's go over the CNN model with 16 layers. The model starts with a pair of convolutional layers, each with 32 filters and a kernel size of (5, 5), employing the 'relu' activation function. Following each convolutional layer, a max-pooling layer with a pool size of (2, 2) is added to downsample the spatial dimensions. To mitigate overfitting, dropout regularization with a rate of 0.25 is applied after the max-pooling layers. The pattern repeats with two more sets of convolutional layers and max-pooling, gradually increasing the number of filters to 64 and then 128. The model is then flattened before transitioning into fully connected layers, with a Dense layer of 256 neurons activated by 'relu', and another dropout layer with a rate of 0.5. Finally, the output layer consists of 10 neurons (for each digit) with the 'softmax' activation function.

In [ ]:
cnn_16_layers = Sequential()

cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(5, 5), padding='Same', activation='relu', input_shape=(28, 28, 1)))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(5, 5), padding='Same', activation='relu'))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
cnn_16_layers.add(Dropout(0.25))

cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='Same', activation='relu'))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='Same', activation='relu'))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
cnn_16_layers.add(Dropout(0.25))

cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='Same', activation='relu'))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='Same', activation='relu'))
cnn_16_layers.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
cnn_16_layers.add(Dropout(0.25))

cnn_16_layers.add(layers.Flatten())
cnn_16_layers.add(Dense(256, activation="relu"))
cnn_16_layers.add(Dropout(0.5))
cnn_16_layers.add(Dense(10, activation="softmax"))

🖼️ Data Augmentation¶

Now, we are going to incorporate data augmentation using the ImageDataGenerator to enhance the robustness and generalization of the neural network model. I have decided to incorporate data augmentation only for the 16-layer CNN model. The purpose of this is to make our final model as good as possible, using different techniques. Data augmentation involves applying various transformations to our existing dataset, creating new, slightly modified versions of the images. This helps the model become more resilient to diverse writing styles and orientations, reducing the risk of overfitting to specific patterns in the training data. The specified transformations, such as random rotations, zooming, and shifts, simulate real-world variations in handwritten digits. By exposing the model to these augmented images during training, we aim to improve its ability to accurately recognize digits in varying conditions, ultimately enhancing its performance on unseen data.

Now that we have explained the importance of data augmentation, it is important to note that there are different parameters of the 'ImageDataGenerator'. Let's delve into our parameters and see what they mean:

  • featurewise_center / samplewise_center: These parameters control whether to center the pixel values of the entire dataset or each individual sample around zero.
  • featurewise_std_normalization / samplewise_std_normalization: These parameters control whether to normalize the pixel values of the entire dataset or each individual sample based on their standard deviation.
  • zca_whitening: This is a method that linearly decorrelates features.
  • rotation_range: Randomly rotates images within the specified range. In our case 10 degrees.
  • zoom_range: Randomly zooms into or out of images.
  • width_shift_range / height_shift_range: Randomly shifts images horizontally or vertically. In our case, the parameters are set to 0.1, which means that image can be shifted horizontally or vertically by a maximum of 10% of its total width.
  • horizontal_flip / vertical_flip: Randomly flips images horizontally or vertically.

To conclude, the parameters chosen for data augmentation in our model have proven to be optimal for enhancing performance. Extensive experimentation with different configurations revealed that the selected values consistently gave the best results. These parameters strike a balance between introducing variability in digit representations and preventing the generation of unrealistic images. The impact of data augmentation is particularly noteworthy, as without it, the model makes approximately 8000 errors, whereas with augmentation, the error count reduces significantly to around 280. This substantial reduction in errors underscores the effectiveness of data augmentation in improving the model's ability to generalize and recognize handwritten digits accurately. The chosen parameters reflect a well-tailored approach to preparing the dataset for training, contributing significantly to the overall success of the digit recognition model.

In [ ]:
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
        featurewise_center=False,
        samplewise_center=False,
        featurewise_std_normalization=False,
        samplewise_std_normalization=False,
        zca_whitening=False,
        rotation_range=10,
        zoom_range = 0.1,
        width_shift_range=0.1,
        height_shift_range=0.1,
        horizontal_flip=False,
        vertical_flip=False
        )

In conclusion, our exploration of neural networks revealed a progression in model performance. The initial feedforward neural network served as a solid introduction, demonstrating satisfactory results despite its simplicity. Moving to our first convolutional neural network (CNN) marked a significant improvement, showcasing enhanced accuracy and reduced errors. CNNs, known for their prowess in image recognition, proved highly effective in our digit recognition task. The first CNN model showed extremely good results and proved that simplicity sometimes leads to really good results. However, the pinnacle of our exploration was the final CNN model, boasting 16 layers and coupled with Data Augmentation. This model achieved the best results, minimizing errors and affirming the power of deeper architectures and data augmentation techniques. It's essential to acknowledge once again that some digits in the dataset pose challenges even for human recognition, emphasizing the significance of the achieved results. Collectively, all three models played pivotal roles in our tasks of digit recognition and in-depth exploration of neural networks.

🤝 Conclusion¶

In conclusion of the project, I would like to say first that the whole process was extremely fun and entertaining. The domain of neural networks was fun to me and it was really interesting to explore. Due to the time limit, my project is not as big as the previous one, but nonetheless I think I achieved good results. I was following the AI project methodology once again in my structure. I took my time to explore the data and the handwritten digits themselves. This step was crucial for me to understand better what results to expect. Not all digits in the dataset are recognizable, but the models managed to perform good. As for the neural networks, I started by implementing a really simple model as an introduction to the topic. This model helped me understand how exactly neural networks work. Afterwards, I continued with more complex models that are CNNs. With my last model, in combination with data augmentation, I managed to get the best results, as I finetuned the parameters and tried out different options and variations. As for the results, all models performed good, none of them are overfitting after I regulazied them, but the last model gave the best perfomance and minimum errors. The errors on the last model vary between 250-290 out of 10,000 which is a really good result in my opinion, considering the fact that some of the digits are hard to be recognized even by a human. A future improvement to minimize the errors more would be creating an even more complex model by initializing more epochs (for example 100) or creating an ensemble method. Due to the time limit, these aspects were not included in my original scope of the project. My goal was to understand neural networks and lay a foundation for more advanced AI topics in the future. I achieved my goal, I had fun throughout the process and enjoyed the handwritten digits domain.
